#Cleaning and removing stopwords
STOPWORDS = set(stopwordlist)
def cleaning_stopwords(tweet):
    return " ".join([word for word in str(tweet).split() if word not in STOPWORDS])
dataset['tweet'] = dataset['tweet'].apply(lambda tweet: cleaning_stopwords(tweet))

#Compute and plot the Confusion matrix
cf_matrix = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_train)
categories = ['Negative','Positive']
group_names = ['True Neg','False Pos', 'False Neg','True Pos']
group_percentages = ['{0:.2%}'.format(value) for value in cf_matrix.flatten() / np.sum(cf_matrix)]
labels = [f'{v1}n{v2}' for v1, v2 in zip(group_names,group_percentages)]
labels = np.asarray(labels).reshape(2,2)

MODEL ASSESSMENT

We can draw the following conclusions after analysing each model, i.e.

1)Accuracy: In terms of model accuracy, Logistic Regression outperforms SVM, which in turn outperforms Bernoulli Naive Bayes.

2)F1-score: The class 0 and class 1 F1 Scores are as follows: (a) For class 0, Bernoulli Naive Bayes, SVM, and Logistic Regression all had accuracy values of 0.90, 0.91, and 0.92, respectively. (b) For class 1, Bernoulli Naive Bayes, SVM, and Logistic Regression all had accuracy values of 0.66, 0.68, and 0.69, respectively.

3) AUC Score: The ROC-AUC scores for all three models are identical.

Therefore, we conclude that the optimal model for the aforementioned dataset is the Logistic Regression.
